<subSubSection id="C36CDAD58D29FFE7B5EAFD82FA7EFD39" box="[151,1436,618,645]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="8BC9895E8D29FFE7B5EAFD82FA7EFD39" blockId="17.[151,1437,618,1905]" box="[151,1436,618,645]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">
<heading id="D0813E328D29FFE7B5EAFD82FA7EFD39" bold="true" box="[151,1436,618,645]" centered="true" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D29FFE7B5EAFD82FA7EFD39" bold="true" box="[151,1436,618,645]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">
<taxonomicName id="4C76F2DD8D29FFE7B5EAFD82FED7FD39" authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[151,309,618,645]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D29FFE7B5EAFD82FED7FD39" bold="true" box="[151,309,618,645]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Lysmata rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is native to the Indo-Pacific and introduced in its 
<materialsCitation id="3B1E83038D29FFE7B60FFD82FA7EFD39" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3804716302" box="[882,1436,618,645]" country="Brazil" location="Atlantic" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="holotype">
<typeStatus id="54CD37FC8D29FFE7B60FFD82FC47FD39" box="[882,933,619,645]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">type</typeStatus>
locality (
<collectingCountry id="F361C9CE8D29FFE7B172FD83FBB8FD38" box="[1039,1114,618,644]" name="Brazil" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Brazil</collectingCountry>
) and the 
<location id="8EA9DF858D29FFE7B1BCFD83FAC3FD38" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03DF38488D29FFE7B5EAFD82FC4BF8CD:8EA9DF858D29FFE7B1BCFD83FAC3FD38" box="[1217,1313,618,644]" country="Brazil" name="Atlantic" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Atlantic</location>
as a whole
</materialsCitation>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36CDAD58D29FFE7B5EAFD66FE33FB79" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC9895E8D29FFE7B5EAFD66FE33FB79" blockId="17.[151,1437,618,1905]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">
At present, determining the natural distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="4C76F2DD8D29FFE7B7A1FD66FCD3FD15" authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[732,817,655,681]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D29FFE7B7A1FD66FCD3FD15" box="[732,817,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is confounded by the discovery of a phylogenetically close and currently undescribed species (
<emphasis id="B902554C8D29FFE7B712FD5AFD64FD70" box="[623,646,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L.</emphasis>
sp. AUS2) collected from north 
<collectingCountry id="F361C9CE8D29FFE7B17FFD5AFB8EFD71" box="[1026,1132,691,717]" name="Australia" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Australia</collectingCountry>
, which is morphologically similar (albeit with some differences in the number of carpal and meral second pereopod segments) and likely possesses a similar coloration pattern (thin red stripes with dark transverse bands on the pleon). Although we do not know the coloration pattern of the Australian individuals included in the present study, photographs of Australian “ 
<taxonomicName id="4C76F2DD8D29FFE7B5D9FCAAFEEBFCE0" baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[164,265,835,860]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D29FFE7B5D9FCAAFEEBFCE0" box="[164,265,835,860]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE7F4AF8D29FFE7B459FCAAFDF4FCE1" author="Vaughan, D. B. &amp; Grutter, A. S. &amp; Hutson, K. S." box="[292,534,835,861]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="429 - 436" refId="ref24336" refString="Vaughan, D. B., Grutter, A. S. &amp; Hutson, K. S. (2018 a) Cleaner shrimp remove parasite eggs on fish cages. Aquaculture Environment Interactions, 10, 429 - 436. https: // doi. org / 10.3354 / AEI 00280" type="journal article" year="2018">
Vaughan 
<emphasis id="B902554C8D29FFE7B4F2FCAAFE25FCE1" box="[399,455,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">et al.</emphasis>
2018a
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE7F4AF8D29FFE7B75CFCAAFD0FFCE1" author="Barton, J. A. &amp; Humphrey, C. &amp; Bourne, D. G. &amp; Hutson, K. S." box="[545,749,835,861]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="61 - 66" refId="ref17900" refString="Barton, J. A., Humphrey, C., Bourne, D. G. &amp; Hutson, K. S. (2020) Biological controls to manage Acropora - eating flatworms in coral aquaculture. Aquaculture Environment Interactions, 12, 61 - 66. https: // doi. org / 10.3354 / aei 00347" type="journal article" year="2020">
Barton 
<emphasis id="B902554C8D29FFE7B709FCAAFD4EFCE1" box="[628,684,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">et al.</emphasis>
2020
</bibRefCitation>
) are similar to photographs/illustrations of 
<taxonomicName id="4C76F2DD8D29FFE7B1AFFCAAFAC4FCE1" authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[1234,1318,835,861]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D29FFE7B1AFFCAAFAC4FCE1" box="[1234,1318,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="F361C9CE8D29FFE7B017FCAAFF51FC3D" name="Brazil" pageId="17" pageNumber="206">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFE7F4AF8D29FFE7B5BEFC8EFDFBFC3D" author="Laubenheimer, H. &amp; Rhyne, A. L." box="[195,537,871,897]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="298 - 304" refId="ref21261" refString="Laubenheimer, H. &amp; Rhyne, A. L. (2010) Lysmata rauli, a new species of peppermint shrimp, (Decapoda: Hippolytidae) from the southwestern Atlantic. Zootaxa, 2372 (1), 298 - 304. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2372.1.23" type="journal article" year="2010">Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne 2010</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE7F4AF8D29FFE7B758FC8EFCF2FC3D" author="Soledade, G. O. &amp; Baeza, J. A. &amp; Boehs, G. &amp; Simoes, S. M. &amp; Santos, P. S. &amp; Da Costa, R. C. &amp; Almeida, A. O. &amp; Souza Santos, P. &amp; Caetano da Costa, R. &amp; Almeida, A. O." box="[549,784,871,897]" pageId="17" pageNumber="206" pagination="66 - 77" refId="ref23416" refString="Soledade, G. O., Baeza, J. A., Boehs, G., Simoes, S. M., Santos, P. S., Da Costa, R. C., Almeida, A. O., Souza Santos, P., Caetano da Costa, R. &amp; Almeida, A. O. (2013) A precautionary tale when describing species in a world of invaders: morphology, coloration and genetics demonstrate that Lysmata rauli is not a new species endemic to Brazil but a junior synonym of the Indo-Pacific L. vittata. Journal of Crustacean Biology, 33 (1), 66 - 77. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 1937240 X- 00002122" type="journal article" year="2013">
Soledade 
